<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1436,151,213]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Geographic distribution. Mediterranean, Eastern Atlantic, and 
<collectingRegion box="[917,1032,151,177]" inferredBySuffix="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Black Sea</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Vasil'eva, E. D." box="[1050,1227,151,177]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" refId="ref65796" refString="Vasil'eva, E. D. (2007) Fish of the Black Sea. Key to marine, brackish-water, euryhaline, and anadromous species with color illustrations, collected by S. V. Bogorodsky. VNIRO Publishing, Moscow, 237 pp. [in Russian, with English abstract]" type="book" year="2007">Vasil’eva 2007</bibRefCitation>
). This species has migrated to the 
<collectingRegion box="[328,379,187,213]" country="Papua New Guinea" name="Gulf" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Gulf</collectingRegion>
of 
<collectingRegion box="[416,473,187,213]" country="Egypt" name="As Suways" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Suez</collectingRegion>
, in the 
<collectingRegion box="[555,647,187,213]" country="Eritrea" name="Semenawi Keyih Bahri" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Red Sea</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Goren, M. &amp; Klausewitz, W." box="[662,962,187,213]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="19 - 24" refId="ref55531" refString="Goren, M. &amp; Klausewitz, W. (1978) Two Mediterranean gobiid fishes new in the Red Sea (Pisces: Gobiidae). Senckenbergiana Biologica, 59, 19 - 24." type="journal article" year="1978">Goren &amp; Klausewitz 1978</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
